                        <interp inst="t18290611-315-victim2248" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-315-off1657 t18290611-315-victim2248"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , in her dwelling-house
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-315-person2249">
                  ANN 
                  ISTED
               <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2249" type="surname" value="ISTED"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2249" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2249" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am cook to Charlotte 
               <persName id="t18290611-315-person2250">
                  Matilda 
                  Bernard
               <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2250" type="surname" value="Bernard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2250" type="given" value="Matilda"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2250" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , commonly called Lady Bernard, who lives in <placeName id="t18290611-315-crimeloc1660">Bryanstone-place, Bryanstone-square, in the parish of Marylebone</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-315-crimeloc1660" type="placeName" value="Bryanstone-place, Bryanstone-square, in the parish of Marylebone"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-315-crimeloc1660" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-315-off1657 t18290611-315-crimeloc1660"></join>. On the 4th of May, between three and four o'clock in the afternoon. I lost this plate from the pantry - the area door was shut too - I was out, and as I came in I met the prisoner in the passage of the house with the plate; I came in at the area door - he was carrying it in his hand; I asked what he did with that, caught hold of him, and shoved him back: I screamed out, and he let the plate fall on the mat - I stooped to pick it up and he ran past me; the footman ran after him - he was quite a stranger.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CLARKSON. Q. Is Lady 
               <persName id="t18290611-315-person2251">Bernard</persName>
             a Peeress? A. She is a <rs id="t18290611-315-viclabel1661" type="occupation">Baronet's widow</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-315-victim2248 t18290611-315-viclabel1661"></join>; I have been fifteen months with her, and heard her state her Christian names.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-315-person2252">
                  JOHN 
                  HOBBS
               <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2252" type="surname" value="HOBBS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2252" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2252" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am butler to her ladyship. The plate was all safe in the footman's pantry at three o'clock - I heard the cook scream out, came down stairs, and saw the prisoner running by the iron railing; I ran after him, and took him about one hundred and fifty yards from the house; the plate was lying on the mat; I found the cupboard and the pantrydoors open; here is the plate; here are eight spoons, worth 4l.; two ladles, worth 18s.; three forks, worth 28, and one pair of sugar tongs, worth 5s., that is the market price - it is worth more than that; I have had it weighed since, and swear it is worth 6l.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. You did not see him till he was running? A. No; the cook pointed him out - I did not see his face.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-315-person2253">
                  ANN 
                  ISTED
               <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2253" type="surname" value="ISTED"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2253" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2253" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am sure he is the man - I never lost sight of him till I pointed him out.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-315-person2254">
                  JOSEPH 
                  STRIDE
               <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2254" type="surname" value="STRIDE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2254" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-315-person2254" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I heard the alarm given, and saw the prisoner come out of the area steps, and stopped him myself without losing sight of him; I am servant to Mr. Martin, of Bryanstone-square - he gave me the sugar tongs out of his pocket.</p>
               <p>Three witnesses gave the prisoner a good character.</p>
               <p>
